# Report generator script: Suricatoos Premium PDF.
#
# This report generator initially creates a LaTeX file using a XML
# transformation with the tool xsltproc. In a second step the LaTeX file is
# processed with the tool pdflatex which results in the final PDF file. The
# branded logo PDFs that ship in this report format bundle are referenced by
# the stylesheet via \includegraphics and are resolved relative to this
# directory, which is the working directory while the generator runs.
# The intermediate files are stored under a temporary directory.

TMP=`mktemp -d` || exit 1

# Make the bundled logo assets available next to the intermediate .tex file so
# that pdflatex (which runs with -output-directory ${TMP}) can find them.
cp ./suricatoos-*.pdf "${TMP}/" 2>/dev/null

# NB: xsltproc stderr goes to the PER-RUN temp dir, NOT a shared /tmp/err.out.
# The stock template hardcodes /tmp/err.out, which gvmd (running as the non-root
# gvmd user) cannot create/overwrite if another user owns it — that makes the
# whole generator fail with exit 1 and the report downloads as 0 bytes.
#
# The `--stringparam lang <code>` selects the report language (en | pt_BR | es).
# build-feed-xml.py rewrites this exact token per language to produce the three
# per-language report_format objects, so keep it on one line, verbatim.
xsltproc --stringparam lang en ./latex.xsl $1 > ${TMP}/report.tex 2>${TMP}/err.out

pdflatex -interaction batchmode -output-directory ${TMP} ${TMP}/report.tex > /dev/null 2>&1

# Run a second time to resolve references, the table of contents and the
# "page X of Y" page numbering assembled during the first run.
# NB: this MUST run in the FOREGROUND. The stock template backgrounds it with
# "&" + wait, but under gvmd's non-interactive system() shell that wait does not
# reliably block, so the following cat races the second pdflatex still truncating
# report.pdf and the report downloads as 0 bytes. Sequential foreground is robust.
pdflatex -interaction batchmode -output-directory ${TMP} ${TMP}/report.tex > /dev/null 2>&1

cat ${TMP}/report.pdf && rm -rf ${TMP}
